WRITING.TEXT: These are great points but also a huge part of working remotely successfully also depends on the processes your company has in place to support a remote working culture.
I wonder what is more important, a high salary or job satisfaction? That might explain why these more skilled developers get paid less than yourself. Things you don #8217;t like, don #8217;t last.
A good diet and a healthy amount of sleep should help this I have found as I had the same issue. Also, reducing the amount of caffeine intake
What industry do you work in? I could potentially point you in the direction of where to begin looking for remote jobs

I always find go with whatever you #8217;re most comfortable with. There are so many languages or frameworks that people bad mouth, but they have been integral in creating successful products or systems.

After a quick Google search I have come across this, might not be the solutions you #8217;re looking for but it #8217;s a start. https://blog.capterra.com/top-free-and-open-source-hotel-booking-engine-software-solutions-compared/

It sounds like your problem is with meetings rather than video meetings. Each meeting should have an agenda, an objective and possibly actionable points to come out of it. These should accompany the meeting invite so attendees know how to prepare and what to expect. Then, as long as everyone has an acceptable internet connection, mic and camera then the meeting should run smoothly. Like every meeting, they just need structure and purpose. The fact that they #8217;re over video should not make a difference to how effective they are.
Interesting, so why do you think this happened because you're remote? It sounds like if there was a misunderstanding of information then this would have happened when working in an office anyway?
This might also be of interest to you https://twitter.com/fellowapp/status/1245029092963028992?s=21

This is a great resource and thanks for sharing, especially during the difficult times of economic uncertainty. We are seeing more people put on leave that were working for companies that were not prepared for remote working (some it was not possible for, obviously) We are also trying to do our bit to help people who may have been laid off, get back in to work which is why we started [subject5259.com](https://www.subject5259.com) which is focused on developers looking to work 100% remotely. I must also add we are one of many places to find remote working jobs and a quick Google search will surface plenty of other popular resources. Good luck to anyone currently looking for that next opportunity, and thanks again for sharing. Stay safe.

One thing I cannot stress enough when trying to build a cohesive remote team is documentation. I suggest replacing the sticky notes with Trello or Jira tickets, and making sure they have thoroughly been fleshed out with all the information required to carry out the task as well as detailing an acceptance criteria for each task on the ticket. Any questions or queries should be written within a comment on the ticket so others can follow the thread and status of any particular task at any given time. I hope this helps.

**Communication:** * Slack * Microsoft Teams * Twist * Skype **Video calling (In addition to the above whom also include it):** * Google Hangouts * Jitsi * Zoom * Skype **Organisation:** * Trello * Jira * Todoist * Notion * Basecamp * Asana * Float * Google Drive (File sharing/storage) * Dropbox (File sharing/storage) **Screen Recording** * Loom * Jing * QuickTime **Team Enhancements/Culture** * HeyTaco (Reward based system intergrates with Slack etc) * [Donut.com](https://Donut.com) (Randomly matches you with colleagues to catch up with)
I #8217;d also love to see https://www.subject5259.com on this list. Catering JUST for software developers looking their next remote job.
Sounds similar to this? https://www.npmjs.com/package/deepnested
Great work! I would love to get these added to our site subject5259.com, it #8217;s free and will help spread the word about these positions.
Funnily enough we are working on that as we speak haha. Thanks for the feedback!
Thanks for your through reply and tips on how to deal with interview problems. I will be sure to check out your article, thanks!

A great point made here. Often people a reluctant to apply for roles because they just aren #8217;t sure if it #8217;s right for them. If that is the case, they should use it as an opportunity to interview the company to find out if it #8217;s the right role for them and gain experience. Candidates always think they are the only ones who are getting interviewed when really it should always be a chance for them to interview the company.
Thank you for such a thorough reply. This is incredibly helpful
It would be great to get [EmployRemotely.com](https://www.subject5259.com/) added to this great list of resources! Thanks for putting this together for everyone.
